    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is creatine safe long-term?</summary>
      <p>Yes. 30+ years of safety data show no adverse effects on kidneys, liver, or cardiovascular health in healthy adults. The ISSN, ACSM, and FDA recognize creatine as safe at 3-5g daily. The kidney damage myth is unsupported by clinical evidence.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can creatine gummies replace powder?</summary>
      <p>Yes, if they deliver 3-5g daily. The creatine molecule is identical. The trade-off: gummies cost 10-30x more per serving than powder. Gummies suit those who value convenience over cost. Powder suits those who prioritize value.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does creatine work for women?</summary>
      <p>Yes. A 2021 review found creatine improved women's upper body strength by 20-25% and lower body strength by 15-20%. It does not cause masculine bulking — intracellular water retention creates a toned appearance. Women may also benefit from cognitive and bone health effects.</p>
    </details>

